## Why This Is Asked
This tests practical CAPA design for data segregation issues in multi-tenant exports, focusing on traceability and measurable containment.

## Key Concepts
- CAPA data model
- Lifecycle state machine
- Minimal REST API design
- Metrics to prove effectiveness
- RCA templates and canary-based remediation

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal Express route to create CAPA
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());
let caps = [];
app.post('/caps', (req,res)=>{ const cap = req.body; cap.id = cap.id || String(Date.now()); caps.push(cap); res.status(201).json(cap);});
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you store and attach evidence files?
- How would you enforce tenant isolation in the API and data store?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design CAPA from data governance, not just incident response.

## Key Concepts
- CAPA data model for evidence, artifacts, and policy checks
- Lifecycle state machine with DETECT → INVESTIGATE → CONTAIN → REMEDIATE → VERIFY → CLOSED
- Minimal REST API design for CAPA creation/update with linked traces
- Region-aware compliance metrics (violation rate, MTTR, FP rate)
- RCA template and canary rollout with automated data redaction

## Code Example
```javascript
// CAPA data model sketch (TypeScript)
type CAPARecord = {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  evidenceUrls: string[];
  policyChecks: string[];
  region: string;
  state: 'DETECTED'|'INVESTIGATING'|'CONTAINED'|'REMEDIATED'|'VERIFIED'|'CLOSED';
  createdAt: string;
  updatedAt: string;
};
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you surface policy checks in runtime dashboards?
- How would you automate data redaction in canary tests before broader rollout?

